<CaseStudy slug="should-i-automate-this">
  <p class="lead reveal">The fastest way to burn trust in an AI rollout is to automate the wrong task and let it fail loudly. So I built the opposite of a hype machine: a short decision tool that asks a handful of honest questions and tells you whether a task is a good fit for AI right now, or whether you should leave it alone.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">A calibrated router, not a vibe</h2>
  <p class="reveal">You answer a few questions about the task: how repetitive it is, how much judgment it needs, what it costs to be wrong. Those run through a calibrated router that returns a <strong>tier</strong>, from "automate this today" down to "keep a human on it." The routing logic is pinned by ten golden cases, so the same task always lands in the same place.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">It hands you a stop-test</h2>
  <p class="reveal">A recommendation you cannot check is just an opinion. Every verdict comes with a concrete <strong>stop-test</strong>: the specific condition under which you should pull the automation back. That turns "should I automate this" from a one-time guess into something you can monitor and reverse, which is what makes it safe to act on.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">Honest by construction</h2>
  <p class="reveal">The whole tool is 28 tests green, including the ten calibration goldens and a round-trip check on the shareable result link. It runs entirely in the browser, with nothing to log into and no data leaving the page. Share a verdict by URL and the recipient sees exactly what you saw.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">Why I point to this one</h2>
  <p class="reveal">Good enablement is as much about what you talk people out of as what you sell them on. This tool is the honest half of the job in a single page: it will tell a stakeholder "not yet," and it will tell them why, and it will give them the test that changes the answer.</p>
</CaseStudy>
